on the Gulf in Naklua, ~10–15 minutes from Central Pattaya. About ฿500, 1.5–2 hours. The most iconic single sight in Pattaya — best for photographers, tight schedules and tight budgets."}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Nong Nooch Tropical Garden", "description": "A 600-acre garden park 40 minutes south toward Sattahip, with formal gardens, a dinosaur valley, an elephant show and a Thai cultural show. About ฿700–800, a half-day. Best for families, garden lovers and a fuller, relaxed outing."}]}, {"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "Is the Sanctuary of Truth or Nong Nooch better?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Neither is universally better — they're different attractions. The Sanctuary of Truth is one stunning hand-carved teak temple you see in 1.5–2 hours near town, for about ฿500. Nong Nooch is a 600-acre garden park with shows and dinosaurs, 40 minutes south, for ฿700–800 and a half-day. Choose the Sanctuary for an iconic quick visit, Nong Nooch for families and variety."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How much do tickets cost for each?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "In 2026, walk-up adult entry to the Sanctuary of Truth is about ฿500 (children around ฿250), covering the temple and grounds. Nong Nooch Tropical Garden runs about ฿700–800 for adults and ฿450–600 for children, which bundles the gardens plus the elephant and cultural shows. Booking online ahead usually saves 10–20% at either."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Which is better for families with kids?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Nong Nooch, comfortably. The elephant show, 4D dinosaur valley, buggy tour and open lawns keep children busy for hours, making it one of Pattaya's best family days out. The Sanctuary of Truth impresses older kids with its scale but is mainly a walk-and-look visit, so toddlers tend to lose interest within half an hour."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How long does each visit take?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Plan 1.5 to 2 hours at the Sanctuary of Truth — it's a single building, so you absorb it and take photos fairly quickly. Nong Nooch deserves 3 to 5 hours because of its size and scheduled shows; a rushed two-hour visit there wastes the ticket. If you do both in a day, allow a full, fast day."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How far are they from Central Pattaya?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The Sanctuary of Truth is close — about 8 km and a 10–15 minute drive north into Naklua, near Wong Amat Beach, costing ฿150–250 by Grab. Nong Nooch is roughly 18 km and a 35–45 minute drive south toward Sattahip, so budget ฿300–500 each way by Grab or join a half-day tour."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I visit both in one day?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, and many people do. Start at the Sanctuary of Truth first thing in the morning when it's cool and quiet, then drive south to Nong Nooch for lunch and the afternoon shows. Tickets for both come to roughly ฿1,200–1,400 for an adult. It makes for a full, fairly fast day, so an early start helps."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Do I need to dress modestly at the Sanctuary of Truth?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. The Sanctuary of Truth is treated as a sacred site, so shoulders and knees should be covered. If you arrive in shorts or a tank top, staff at the entrance lend sarongs and cover-ups at no charge. Nong Nooch has no dress code, but comfortable shoes and a hat help on a long, sunny garden walk."}}]}]$b$);
