<!-- HERO -->
<figure class="art-hero"><img alt="Pattaya city beach 1 – Scooter rental vsGrabin Pattaya: which should you use?" fetchpriority="high" height="506" loading="eager" src="../Pattaya-Tum-Gorseller-Resized/pattaya-city-beach-1.webp" width="1100"/>
      <figcaption class="cap"><span class="lead"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-pin"></use></svg> Scooter vs Grab in Pattaya · the freedom of two wheels vs the safety of a back seat, compared honestly</span><span class="credit">Go To Pattaya</span></figcaption></figure>
<!-- TL;DR -->
<div class="tldr">
<h4><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-info"></use></svg> If you only have 30 seconds</h4>
<p><b>Rent a scooter</b> only if you already ride at home, hold an <b>International Driving Permit with a motorcycle category</b>, and want to explore Jomtien, Pratumnak and the back roads on your own schedule — it's the cheapest way to move, around <b>฿200–300/day</b> plus ฿40–60 of fuel. <b>Use Grab</b> (and Bolt) if you've never ridden, if it's your first trip, or if you'll be drinking — fares of <b>฿60–150</b> across town are cheap, metered, door-to-door and keep you off Thailand's most dangerous roads. For most short-stay visitors the honest answer is <b>Grab for the city, scooter only if you're an experienced, licensed rider</b>.</p>
</div>
</div>
